desilinguist (2023-07-12): Never mind @austinorr, it does work! Just realized that I had a bug in how I was using `media_type_extra`. It should be:

```python
media_type_extra={"examples": example_requests["text"]},
```

and not just:
```python
media_type_extra=example_requests["text"],
```

hochstibe (2023-07-13): It worked for me for a body parameter. Should it work as well on other parameter types? I tested with Header, but it was not included in openapi.json (`media_type_extra={"examples": {"e1": {"value": "foo"}}}`).

In my opinion, the `media_type_extra` is good, if you want to give additional context to the examples (like the "summary"). Just for adding one or more examples, it seems a bit clumsy.

Discussion on PR #14036: 👽️ Ensure compatibility with Pydantic 2.12.0

YuriiMotov (2025-09-02): I think we should try to avoid adding new dependency.

Maybe something with `dirty_equals`?
Take a look at the code in the details

<details>

```py
from dirty_equals import IsOneOf

v1 = {
    "age": {
        "title": "Age",
        "anyOf": [
            {"exclusiveMinimum": 0.0, "type": "number"},
            {"type": "string"},
        ],
    }
}

v2 = {
    "age": {
        "title": "Age",
        "anyOf": [
            {"exclusiveMinimum": 0.0, "type": "number"},
            {"type": "string", "pattern": r"^(?!^[-+.]*$)[+-]?0*\d*\.?\d*$"},
        ],
    }
}


expected = {
    "age": {
        "title": "Age",
        "anyOf": [
            {"exclusiveMinimum": 0.0, "type": "number"},
            IsOneOf(
                {"type": "string"},
                {"type": "string", "pattern": r"^(?!^[-+.]*$)[+-]?0*\d*\.?\d*$"}
            ),
        ],
    }
}

assert v1 == expected
assert v2 == expected

```

</details>

cjwatson (2025-09-07): > I think we should try to avoid adding new dependency.
